</figcaption>
</figure>

<h2 id="historic-plaza">Historic Plaza</h2>
<p>San Miguel has many historic buildings that illustrate architecture from different periods.  San Miguel del Vado‚Äôs Plaza is bisected by the Santa Fe Trail and the Pecos River, making it function as two plazas.<sup id="fnref:NRHP7"><a href="#fn:NRHP7" class="footnote">7</a></sup> Two historic buildings remain on the east side of the plaza, the Dance Hall and Zaguan house retain Spanish period characteristics including low windows and wood ceilings. West of the Plaza lies the foundation of the old San Miguel County courthouse and what may have been a hotel.<sup id="fnref:NRHP71"><a href="#fn:NRHP71" class="footnote">8</a></sup>
Southwest of the historic church, metal and ceramic artifacts can still be spotted littering the ground. This is evidence of the gathering and resting place of traders and travelers on the Santa Fe Trail.<sup id="fnref:Jenks3"><a href="#fn:Jenks3" class="footnote">9</a></sup></p>

<h2 id="san-miguel-del-vado-church">San Miguel del Vado Church</h2>
<p>San Miguel del Vado Church is located on the west side of the plaza. The Church is one of the oldest remaining buildings in the Settlement; however, the church‚Äôs architecture is a mix of Spanish colonial, Gothic windows and spires, wood and linoleum floors, and a bell added in 1821, and other modern amenities. Despite these different design influences, the internal structure of the church is the same as when it was built in 1805, and it still functions as the cultural center of the village.<sup id="fnref:NRHP83"><a href="#fn:NRHP83" class="footnote">10</a></sup></p>

<figure class="img-left" style="width:33%">
