<h2 id="santa-fe-trail-after-mexican-independence">Santa Fe Trail after Mexican Independence</h2>
<p>The Santa Fe Trail was utilized by Spanish merchants moving goods between Santa Fe and Mexico City. Mexico gained independence from Spain in 1821 which opened up trade across the Southwest. Trade was limited however, because of heavy taxation between newly formed Mexico and the United States. As tensions rose between the nations, the Santa Fe Trail remained in use. The trail was used by U.S. General Stephen W. Kearny during the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capture_of_Santa_Fe">seizure of Santa Fe</a> in August 1846. General Kearny took control of San Miguel del Vado before reaching Santa Fe. The <a href="https://home.nps.gov/safe/learn/historyculture/map-timeline-2.htm">Mexican American War</a> ended in 1846 with the signing of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Guadalupe_Hidalgo">Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo</a> and the New Mexcio Territory became a part of the United States.</p>

<figure class="img-right" style="width:33%">
